{"total":11990,"quota_max":10000,"quota_remaining":9833,"has_more":true,"items":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c834d76c96312d5bd96a7c6172289113?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13294,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13294/teusz","reputation":110,"display_name":"Teusz"},"closed_date":1449823652,"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c5f6d535d5548db913337c44ec4e1d09?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20502,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20502/stefan","reputation":72,"display_name":"stefan"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449796173,"creation_date":1449615606,"body":"<p>Normally Humans inherit from each parent one sex determine Chromosome. If you have a XX chromosome pair you are female. If you have a XY pair you are male. Therefore the Y-Chromosome get only passed on from father to son. The Chromosomes itself consist of DNA. The DNA consists of base pairs in which an A only pairs with a T and a C only pairs with a G. The Y-Chromosome has about 57 million of these base pairs. DNA is normally relative stable but from time to time only one of these base pairs randomly changes from a C-G base pair to an A-T base pair. This phenomenon is called a pointmutation. So imagen two brothers. One has the unchanged Y-Chromosome of their father the other has one this pointmutations. So the descendants of the one Brother have the same Y-Chromosome, with exception of the pointmutation, the same Y-Chromosome. This is called a Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms (SNP). In the millennia the Y-Chromosomes acquire more and more of these SNPs. One combination of these SNPs is called a Haplogroup. By the amount of SNPs and the kind of them you can reconstruct which Haplogroup descended from which one. You have the Haplogroup R-M512 which is a rather old one (<a href=\"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d4/R1a._Info-19.05.2014.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d4/R1a._Info-19.05.2014.jpg<\/a>) and could be found in great area. M512 is actually the name of the last SNP that defines your Haplogroup. Here some people had write down which Haplogroup they belong to. By the ethnicity of the name you can assume how far it is spread ( <a href=\"https://www.familytreedna.com/public/R1a?iframe=ysnp\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.familytreedna.com/public/R1a?iframe=ysnp<\/a> ).\nAnother Name would be R1a1a. Maybe these papers help you more to understand the nomenclature ( <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC155271/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC155271/<\/a>  <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1288547/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1288547/<\/a> ).<br>\nShort tandem repeats (STR) are small DNA sequences that repeat multiple times.  On the Y-Chromosome these STR can be referred to as DNA Y-chromosome Segments (DYS).  DYS448 has the sequence AGAGAT  with 20 to 26 repeats. Here ( <a href=\"http://cstl.nist.gov/strbase/ystrpos1.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://cstl.nist.gov/strbase/ystrpos1.htm<\/a> ) is visualized where actually  it is located on the Y-Chromosome.  In your case the laboratory was not able  to measure any repeats.     <\/p>\n","answer_id":41354,"question_id":41229,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1449796173}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41229/what-does-it-mean-to-have-a-y-dna-haplogroup-r-m512","last_activity_date":1449796173,"creation_date":1449227203,"answer_count":1,"title":"What does it mean to have a Y-DNA Haplogroup \"R-M512\"?","body":"<p>I did a DNA test to learn about my origins, but the results are highly technical.<\/p>\n\n<p>I see I have a Y-DNA Haplogroup R-M512 and a mutation (zero marker in DYS448). I Googled these terms and came across a bunch of technical papers, but I don't have the expertise in Genetics to make much sense of them. <\/p>\n\n<p>I wonder if one of you can shed light on this?<\/p>\n","question_id":41229,"tags":["genetics","human-genetics"],"score":0,"accepted_answer_id":41354,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"off-topic","is_answered":true,"view_count":332,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e9c675dd9408721a8e8e1106774a9d11?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20512,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20512/user3004041","reputation":28,"display_name":"user3004041"},"closed_date":1449647101,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":1,"post_id":41342,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449606825,"comment_id":70109,"body":"Welcome to Bio. Are you askinh whether Arg and Gln are different amono acids??"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41342,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449782674,"comment_id":70248,"body":"Great edit - @Roland has given the right answer - see the official <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Class/MLACourse/Modules/MolBioReview/iupac_aa_abbreviations.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">IUPAC website<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"moderator","user_id":5144,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5144/chris","reputation":31001,"display_name":"Chris"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449604513,"creation_date":1449604513,"body":"<p>The reason is simple: These are two different amino acids with different side chains. They look very similar, but they are not:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/6vSGR.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/6vSGR.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This is <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glutamine\" rel=\"nofollow\">L-Glutamine<\/a>, its chemical formula is C<sub>5<\/sub>H<sub>10<\/sub>N<sub>2<\/sub>O<sub>3<\/sub>.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/wnB4D.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/wnB4D.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>This is <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asparagine\" rel=\"nofollow\">L-Asparagine<\/a>, its chemical formula is: C<sub>4<\/sub>H<sub>5<\/sub>N<sub>2<\/sub>O<sub>3<\/sub>. This shows that L-Asparagine has one CH<sub>2<\/sub> less than L-Glutamine.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41344,"question_id":41342,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/120150514d16f8c16486e34cdc3f5461?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20513,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20513/viktoria","reputation":41,"display_name":"Viktoria"},"score":4,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449605497,"creation_date":1449605497,"body":"<p>Asparagine (Asn) and glutamine (Gln) are derived forms of the amino acids aspartic acid (Asp) and glutamic acid (Glu). \nBoth amino acid pairs (Asn/Asp, Gln/Glu) consist of the same carbon backbone, \ntheir side chains only differ in their functional group.\nAspartic and glutamic acid include a carboxylic acid (-COOH), whereas asparagine and glutamine are carboxamides (-CO-NH2).<\/p>\n\n<p>Here you can see asparagine and aspartic acid as example:<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/TGCxR.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/TGCxR.png\" alt=\"Asparagine (Asn)\"><\/a>\nAsparagine (Asn)<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/vR6ZV.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/vR6ZV.png\" alt=\"Aspartic acid (Asp)\"><\/a>\nAspartic acid (Asp)<\/p>\n","answer_id":41345,"question_id":41342,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10152727909540095/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":13336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13336/curioustree","reputation":83,"display_name":"CuriousTree","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":0,"post_id":41346,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449608452,"comment_id":70114,"body":"No, Asx (B) and Glx (Z) are the abbreviations used when there is uncertainty abous Aspartate/Asparagine or Glutamate/Glutamine, respectively."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10152727909540095/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":13336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13336/curioustree","reputation":83,"display_name":"CuriousTree","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":41346,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1449611716,"comment_id":70119,"body":"Okay - In a way that makes more sense. But just because I am curious: I generally trust the NCBI webpage - so why does it refer to them as this in the table? It seems as though the standardized way of writing them (if you have to differentiate between e.g. Glutamine and glutamic acid is Glx and Gln).. What about the one letter code ( B and Z) because that is very specific for glutamine and asparagine, or is it the same with that as well?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":1,"post_id":41346,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449612033,"comment_id":70120,"body":"Look at the NCBI table again. It says that Q is the specific code for glutamine (Gln), and N is the specific code for asparagine (Asn). Asx (B) and Glx (Z) are the abbreviations used for the ambiguous (unspecific) cases. See also my answer above for an explanation of why this occurs."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10152727909540095/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":13336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13336/curioustree","reputation":83,"display_name":"CuriousTree","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":41346,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1449612359,"comment_id":70121,"body":"okay, thanks - that makes perfect sense."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449612446,"creation_date":1449605558,"body":"<p>NCBI Amino Acid Abbreviations (IUPAC): <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Class/MLACourse/Modules/MolBioReview/iupac_aa_abbreviations.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Class/MLACourse/Modules/MolBioReview/iupac_aa_abbreviations.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Glutamine and asparagine are converted into glutamic acid (Gln) and aspartic acid (Asn) by a simple hydrolysis of the amide group, so they are slightly different from each other. In general the amino acids Glutamine and asparagine's amide group (CONH2) are changed to a carboxyl group (COOH).<\/p>\n\n<p>A good answer to this question was also given in this forum, with visualization: <a href=\"https://www.quora.com/Whats-the-difference-between-asparagine-and-aspartic-acid\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.quora.com/Whats-the-difference-between-asparagine-and-aspartic-acid<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":41346,"question_id":41342,"up_vote_count":0,"last_edit_date":1449612446},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/74bcb23ef9e019ed7fe407e8bfa47f5c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":15695,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/15695/roland","reputation":2431,"display_name":"Roland"},"score":4,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449610620,"creation_date":1449610620,"body":"<p>The abbreviation Asx (B) is used if it is uncertain whether the amino acid at a given position in a peptide sequence is Asparagine or Aspartate. Similarly, Glx (Z) is used when there is uncertainty between Glutamine / Glutamate. <\/p>\n\n<p>These two pairs of amino acids can be ambiguous in peptide sequences because Asp/Asn and Glu/Gln differs only by a terminal amide (-NH2) group in the side chain, and this amide group can be spontaneously lost from proteins by a <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deamidation\" rel=\"nofollow\">deamidation<\/a> reaction. When this occurs, asparagine is converted to aspartate/isoaspartate, and glutamine to glutamate/glutamate. These cannot be distinguished from \"real\" aspartate or glutamate by <a href=\"http://actachemscand.org/pdf/acta_vol_04_p0283-0293.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">classic peptide sequencing<\/a>, nor by mass spectrometry, since their mass is identical. Hence, protein sequences obtained directly from protein frequently contains Asx/Glx entries.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41350,"question_id":41342,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449611843,"creation_date":1449611843,"body":"<p>From the reference in the question, the query seems to be asking \"Why does an amino acid have two abbreviations, such as Asn and N for asparagine, and Gln and Q for glutamine?\"<\/p>\n\n<p>This is because both abbreviations are commonly used in the scientific literature.  The longer, 3-letter, abbreviation is useful because it is a recognizable shortening of the amino acid's name.  The 1-letter abbreviation tends to be very arbitrary (e.g. Q for glutamine), so it is not very mnemonic. However, the single letter form is much easier to make use of for long sequences of amino acids, as in giving the sequence of a particular protein.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41351,"question_id":41342,"up_vote_count":0}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41342/why-do-asparagine-and-glutamine-have-two-different-abbreviations","last_activity_date":1449779336,"creation_date":1449602367,"answer_count":5,"title":"Why do asparagine and glutamine have two different abbreviations?","body":"<p>I'm looking at amino acid abbreviations and on every site I visit, asparagine and glutamine have two different abbreviations. Is there a reason for this? Do they represent different forms of the amino acid that may have different properties?<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm looking at the abbreviations on this site as an example: \n<a href=\"http://www.hgmd.cf.ac.uk/docs/cd_amino.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.hgmd.cf.ac.uk/docs/cd_amino.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>On the page, asparagine has an abbreviation of 'N' and an abbreviation of 'B'. The abbreviation 'B' doesn't correspond to a codon so why is it there? <\/p>\n\n<p>Glutamine also has two abbreviations ('Q' and 'Z'). The abbreviation 'Z' doesn't correspond to a codon either.<\/p>\n","question_id":41342,"tags":["proteins","amino-acids"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":41350,"down_vote_count":0,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":true,"view_count":202,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1449779336},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/yKGbF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20571,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20571/nemo","reputation":6,"display_name":"Nemo"},"closed_date":1450154227,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":2,"post_id":41407,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449774101,"comment_id":70241,"body":"Welcome to Bio. Consider posting this on Health.SE"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/yKGbF.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20571,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20571/nemo","reputation":6,"display_name":"Nemo"},"score":1,"post_id":41407,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"edited":false,"creation_date":1449774877,"comment_id":70242,"body":"Sorry. I wasn&#39;t aware of &quot;health.SE&quot;.  Maybe it&#39;s better to close this question then."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":4,"post_id":41407,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449905527,"comment_id":70331,"body":"I&#39;m voting to close this question as off-topic because it may be better of at Health. SE"},{"owner":{