&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":0,"post_id":41405,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449818911,"comment_id":70269,"body":"1) More of the emphasis of degeneration and aging has been placed on mitochondria these days. Telomere length usually almost never enters the equation as most tissue is replenished from Adult Stem Cells that continue to express telomerase. 2) If the information you are interested in has been researched and published, it will have likely been done in either Yeast, C. elegans, or Drosophila, so your best bet is to look for data on studies from those model organisms."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41405/how-do-cell-repair-mechanism-ratios-change-as-they-age","last_activity_date":1449762826,"creation_date":1449762674,"answer_count":0,"title":"How do cell repair mechanism ratios change as they age?","body":"<p>I have seen that embryonic stem cells are shown to use homologous repair for double strand breaks rather then non-homologous end joining (NHEJ). <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3128311/\" rel=\"nofollow\">[1]<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>I am wondering if something also happens to a cell's usage of certain repair mechanisms after diversifying.<\/p>\n\n<p>For instance, is there any evidence that two cells in the same lineage but of different ages (one from a person who is 20, another from someone who is 80) use different ratios of repair mechanisms? Has there been any research on this or is there any indirect data that could support such an idea?<\/p>\n","question_id":41405,"tags":["cell-biology","dna","microbiology"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":35,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1449762826},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/49d0d23657ec45eeb254f56f2a0ff6a3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":86,"link":"http://