keley.edu/bacteria/cyanointro.html\" rel=\"nofollow\"><strong>cyanobacteria<\/strong><\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.staff.uni-giessen.de/~gh1484/actino.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">actinomycetes<\/a> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC241898/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Izaguirre <em>et al<\/em>, 1982<\/a>. Humans detect these earthy and musty odors at concentrations of only a few ng/l. The ability to smell geosmin and 2-methylisoborneol is affected by other factors, such as the presence of chlorine, which <strong>masks<\/strong> odors <a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Andrea_Dietrich/publication/7283169_Aesthetic_issues_for_drinking_water/links/0fcfd5093f3bb80b25000000.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Dietrich, 2006)<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>The capability of organisms to detect microorganisms like cyanobacteria is not trivial, as cyanobacteria produce toxic microcystins with <strong>hepatotoxic<\/strong> and <strong>neurotoxic<\/strong> properties that can cause illness and even death <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2984099/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Blaha <em>et al<\/em>, 2009)<\/a>.   <\/p>\n\n<p>In my opinion, from an evolutionary perspective, it would be more important for survival to taste pollutants in the water than to mask these components by generating a taste to water that could potentially make the detection of toxins less effective. <\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2984099/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Blaha <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Interdiscip Toxicol<\/em> (2009); <strong>2<\/strong>(2): 36\u201341<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Andrea_Dietrich/publication/7283169_Aesthetic_issues_for_drinking_water/links/0fcfd5093f3bb80b25000000.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dietrich, <em>J Water and Health<\/em> (2006); <strong>4<\/strong>(Suppl 1): 11-6<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC241898/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Izaguirre <em>et al<\/em>., <em>Appl Environ Microbiol<\/em> (1982); <strong>43<\/strong>(3): 708\u201314<\/a><\/sub>  <\/p>\n","answer_id":41371,"question_id":41364,"up_vote_count":22,"last_edit_date":1449736725}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41364/why-is-water-flavorless","last_activity_date":1449736725,"creation_date":1449642854,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why is water flavorless?","body":"<p>I <a href=\"http://digitalcommons.calpoly.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1126&amp;context=kine_fac\">read<\/a> recently that humans have an innate preference for sweet-tasting foods. That seems feasible since carbohydrates are necessary for cells to undergo cellular respiration, but why then is water not similarly good-tasting? The thirst mechanism is a very long, multi-step process that ensures that humans intake a sufficient amount of water, and it can be really satisfying to drink water when you're really thirsty, but why is it flavorless if it's so vital to life?<\/p>\n","question_id":41364,"tags":["human-physiology","taste"],"score":20,"accepted_answer_id":41371,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":2913,"up_vote_count":20},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10152727909540095/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":13336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13336/curioustree","reputation":83,"display_name":"CuriousTree","accept_rate":100},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10152727909540095/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":13336,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13336/curioustree","reputation":83,"display_name":"CuriousTree","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":41338,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449668464,"comment_id":70167,"body":"I also found that the trimeric state can be downloaded as &quot;biological assembly&quot;, however, I would still like to know how to do this on my own."}],"ans