.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41368,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/aab100ff1f5268a9b0a0777d1d857c8f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20521,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20521/manny-rodriguez","reputation":13,"display_name":"Manny Rodriguez"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1449665304,"comment_id":70163,"body":"In the 2nd paragraph I try to explain that peripheral nerves are pretty similar all over. And linking peripheral anatomy to subjective percept may be tricky. That&#39;s all I&#39;m saying. 5 more rep and you can upvote :)"}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449665246,"creation_date":1449647146,"body":"<p>Why would peripheral anatomy determine subjective sensation? In the end, the cerebral cortex determines the sensation associated with peripheral input. Rewired hamsters can have visual sensations in their auditory cortex <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC27149/\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Frost <em>et al.<\/em>, 2000)<\/a> and visual sensations through tactile stimulation have been reported in man <a href=\"http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0023264\" rel=\"nofollow\">(Ortiz <em>et al.<\/em>, 2011)<\/a>. <\/p>\n\n<p>The sensations you describe are related to tactile stimulation of peripheral nerves. Peripheral nerves are pretty homogenous, and typically carry a bunch of afferent nerve fibers up to the somatosensory cortex.<\/p>\n\n<p><sub><strong>References<\/strong><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC27149/\" rel=\"nofollow\">Frost <em>et al<\/em>., <em>PNAS<\/em> (2000); <strong>97<\/strong>(20): 11068\u201373<\/a><br>\n<strong>-<\/strong> <a href=\"http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/jou