_answer_id":41358,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":117,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":0,"post_id":7307,"edited":false,"creation_date":1361476596,"comment_id":9066,"body":"Surely the grafted part retains its genetic identity and grows normally (as &quot;lemon&quot; in your example) while the rest of the tree retains its &quot;orange&quot; identity. It is a chimaeric plant. You could think of it like an organ transplant in a mammal."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":0,"post_id":7307,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1320/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1361485894,"comment_id":9071,"body":"@AlanBoyd, yes I imagine it <i>is<\/i> chimerism of some sort. Yet you can take a normal bitter orange tree, cut off most of its branches (not even sure that is necessary) and graft a piece of lemon tree bark onto it. From that day on, the entire tree produces lemons, not oranges. So, somehow the grafted tissue is suppressing the original plant. Not what happens in an organ transplant."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/adba480f757d6888109043eab2374107?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","