=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":4108,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4108/remi-b","reputation":22909,"display_name":"Remi.b","accept_rate":88},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449606975,"creation_date":1449590163,"body":"<p><strong>Source of information<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://evolution.berkeley.edu/evolibrary/home.php\" rel=\"nofollow\">Understanding Evolution<\/a> is a free online introductory course of evolutionary biology that will probably answer these questions.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Main_Page\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia<\/a> will also make a decent job at answering your questions.<\/p>\n\n<p>Any introductory book to evolutionary biology would do it.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>To answer your question<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>phylogeny = phylogenetic tree = evolutionary tree: evolutionary relationship between lineages<\/li>\n<li>phylotype: An observed morphological similarity that is used to classify a group of organisms.<\/li>\n<li>OTU: An observed genetic similarity that is used to classify a group of organisms.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Both OTU and phylotype are often used for asexual lineages where the concept of species poorly apply. See more info on the concept of species <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/39664/how-could-humans-have-interbred-with-neanderthals-if-were-a-different-species/39669#39669\">here<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41333,"question_id":41328,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1449606975}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41328/difference-between-various-evolutionary-terms","last_activity_date":1449614284,"creation_date":1449580039,"answer_count":1,"title":"Difference between various evolutionary terms","body":"<p>Could someone kindly explain me the difference between Phylogeny, Phylogenetic Tree, Evolutionary Trees, Phylotype, Clusters, OTU (Open Taxonomic Units). Or if possible please do suggest me a beginner's book on that said topics.<\/p>\n","question_id":41328,"tags":["evolution","bioinformatics","terminology","reference-request"],"score":-1,"down_vote_count":2,"closed_reason":"unclear what you're asking","is_answered":true,"view_count":56,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1449614284},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e598c77fcd88827e6b7f583fc57eca5f?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":20517,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20517/alan-b","reputation":11,"display_name":"Alan B."},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/jlp4Q.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5198,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5198/anongoodnurse","reputation":12148,"display_name":"anongoodnurse"},"score":1,"post_id":41352,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449623877,"comment_id":70130,"body":"They both appear to be eastern swallowtails (the females can be black or yellow); the yellow one definitely is an ES. I can&#39;t speak to your Brazillian butterflies, but <a href=\"http://vanessa.ent.iastate.edu/contests.htm\" rel=\"nofollow\">butterflies can be aggressively territorial with mid-air fighting<\/a>. Like birds."}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41352/what-are-two-butterflies-doing-when-they-fly-together-hitting-each-other","last_activity_date":1449612421,"creation_date":1449612421,"answer_count":0,"title":"What are two butterflies doing when they fly together, 'hitting' each other?","body":"<p>I've Googled this subject extensively but couldn't get an answer:\nMy country is full of butterflies and moths, I've seen a lot of butterflies performing what looks like some kind of fight or mating ritual: Two butterflies of the same species flying together and 'hitting' each other, and when they do that a noise can be heard, I don't know if it's from the actual 'impact' or a noise they produce, but sometimes it's very loud and resembles an electrical arc.\nI'm extremel