le. I consider both to be good arguments as to why we&#39;ll never find such a thing but I suspect the reality is that the space of possible organisms that might be anatomically possible has never actually been explored because there&#39;s no evolutionarily advantageous pathways that leads there."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1366150120,"creation_date":1366150120,"body":"<p>Shigeta's molecular answer is spot on. However, at the large scale level I think the key problem with a biological wheel needs to be spelled out clearly: how does an organism with separate parts maintain these parts? Let's suppose that an organism evolves a fully rotational joint, how do they then provide nutrients to the tissue on the other side? If they don't provide nutrients how does self-repair in this tissue continue without nutrients?<\/p>\n\n<p>Mind you, I'm not sure that the biological problems with a wheel are the real answer. I'm not sure how a wheel evolves. What's the functional intermediate? How does a semi-connected wheel out-perform a limb? Remember than evolution is canalised by what has gone before.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7938,"question_id":7932,"up_vote_count":9},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3c1c82fa856abde64273477774eec80d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3401,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3401/daleypaley","reputation":261,"display_name":"DaleyPaley"},"score":14,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user3395"},"score":0,"post_id":7941,"edited":false,"creation_date":1366211632,"comment_id":10061,"body":"Thanks. 1) Why &quot;severe&quot;? Since, <i>if<\/i> there is no functional intermediate, I presume it has to happen in one jump, only making it (much) less probable (?). I don&#39;t see how such chances would improve by the severity of the &quot;incentives&quot;. 2) I was thinking along the lines of a some sort of an exoskeleton, that, in time, separates, but does remain pierced through the animal. (Is that unthinkable?) It could have the form of two wheels and an axle. :)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3c1c82fa856abde64273477774eec80d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3401,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3401/daleypaley","reputation":261,"display_name":"DaleyPaley"},"score":1,"post_id":7941,"edited":false,"creation_date":1366236000,"comment_id":10078,"body":"Something as complicated as wheels (if even possible with multicellular animals) could never happen as a result of a single, lucky mutation. The term &#39;exaptation&#39; is where evolution takes an existing functional unit, and starts using it for a different purpose. It takes many generations so the evolutionary pressure would have to be sustained. It would have to be severe to be more beneficial than just sticking with legs."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1366179277,"creation_date":1366179277,"body":"<p>In your question, you mention frozen lakes and rightly say that skates would be far easier than wheels, but you could have used salt flats as an example.<\/p>\n\n<p>I think the reason there are no actual wheels is a mixture of ontogenetic and phylogentic barriers, maintenance (nutrition), lubrication and control (nerve connections). There would have to be severe and sustained evolutionary incentives to go from something simple, cheap and extant (legs) to something way more difficult and complex.<\/p>\n\n<p>However, there are several species of plants and animals that use rolling as a form of locomotion. Tumbleweeds are a good example of plants, and for animals, there are <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bzAF7WuXhKA\">spiders<\/a>, <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HmLS2WXZQxU\">caterpillars and salamanders<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p>It only takes a small evolutionary development to take something like this from a passive motion (rolling down hill to escape predators) to active (perhaps creating waves of flexion to roll like... ahem, caterpillar tracks).<\/p>\n","answer_id":7941,"question_id":7932,"up_vote_count":14},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/280c38f4cc343f0f3be19b35d2195c91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":11736,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/11736/jamesqf","reputation":401,"display_name":"jamesqf"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1427825291,"creation_date":1427825291,"body":"<p>There's a basic philosophical problem with asking why there aren't such-and-such.  We could as easily ask why there are no six-limbed vertebrates, or creatures that use hydrogen to fly like balloons.  It's not (necessarily) that they're mechanically or biologically impossible, it's just that evolution started down another pathway first, and (by changing the nature of the \"adjacent possible\") that closed off the paths that led to such creatures.<\/p>\n","answer_id":30947,"question_id":7932,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7932/why-are-there-no-wheeled-animals","last_activity_date":1449552747,"creation_date":1366124708,"answer_count":4,"title":"Why are there no wheeled animals?","body":"<p>In physics, \"almost everything is already discovered, and all that remains is to fill a few unimportant holes.\" (See <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philipp_von_Jolly\">Jolly<\/a>.) Therefore, on Physics SE, people are veering off into different directions: <em>biology<\/em>, for example.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thus, it happens that <a href=\"http://physics.stackexchange.com/q/61174/17609\">a question about bicycles<\/a> generates some discussion about evolution in biology and animals with wheels.<\/p>\n\n<p>Three explanations are offered for the apparent lack of wheely animals (also on <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotating_locomotion_in_living_systems#Biological_barriers_to_wheeled_organisms\">Wikipedia<\/a>, where, by the way, most Physics SE questions are answered perfectly).<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>Evolutionary constraints: \"[A] complex structure or system will not evolve if its incomplete form provides no benefit to an organism.\"<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Developmental and anatomical constraints.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Wheels have significant disadvantages (e.g., when not on roads).<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p>Now, I suggest that all three can be \"solved\".<\/p>\n\n<ol>\n<li><p>With time.<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>With a symbiotic relationship between a wheel-like animal and a \"driver\"-like animal, although this gets awfully close to a <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=R8XAlSp838Y\">\"driver\"-animal<\/a> to jump onto an actual (man-made) wheel. (So, perhaps, you can suggest a better loophole around this constraint.)<\/p><\/li>\n<li><p>Roads are presumably not the only ecological niche where animals with wheels could thrive. I'm thinking of frozen lakes, although there skates would be better than wheels.<\/p><\/li>\n<\/ol>\n\n<p><strong>What, therefore, is <em>the<\/em> explanation for there not being any wheeled animals?\nPlease consider, in your answer, the counterfactual: What assumption of yours would be falsified once a wheely animal <em>is<\/em> discovered?<\/strong><\/p>\n","question_id":7932,"tags":["evolution","zoology","speculative"],"score":50,"accepted_answer_id":7937,"down_vote_count":1,"protected_date":1427817343,"is_answered":true,"view_count":3621,"up_vote_count":51,"last_edit_date":1375453056},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/92ceeb5ba6ba34b154503d6492313cd2?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20481,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20481/akinuri","reputation":111,"display_name":"akinuri"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449538998,"creation_date":1449538998,"body":"<p><em>Fainting, passing out,<\/em> and <em>blacking out<\/em> are all common terms for the same thing, a sudden loss of consciousness of short duration.  The medical term for this is <em><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syncope_(medicine)\" rel=\"nofollow\">syncope<\/a><\/em>. It is caused by a decrease in blood flow to the brain, limiting the the availability of oxygen and nutrients to the brain cells.  Brain cells have high energy requirements, so this causes them to stop functioning, causing loss of consciousness and muscle tone.<\/p>\n\n<p>There are many causes of syncope.  In the situation mentioned, a likely possibility is a pressure change in the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carotid_sinus\" rel=\"nofollow\">carotid sinus<\/a> which is located at the side of the neck. When sensed by a nerve, this can cause primitive parts of the nervous system to change the dilation of blood vessels and the beating of the heart in a manner that brings on syncope.<\/p>\n\n<p>Dreaming during syncope is not uncommon and that fact may be useful in distinguishing syncope from epileptic seizures according to <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21518146\" rel=\"nofollow\">research by Chiesa <em>et al.<\/em><\/a>. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41317,"question_id":41305,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41305/dreaming-after-passing-out","last_activity_date":1449538998,"creation_date":1449525597,"answer_count":1,"title":"Dreaming after passing out","body":"<p>I'll have few questions about passing out and dreaming. English is not my native language, and my biology knowledge is very limited. So bear with me.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>What exactly is blackout? (in a really simple way)<\/li>\n<li>Are there different types of blackout? (see below)<\/li>\n<li>Do fainting, passing out, and blacking out mean the same thing?<\/li>\n<li>Can someone have a dream/vision after loosing consciousness? (during blackout?)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>I'm asking these because I had a similar experience and I'm trying to make sense of it.<\/p>\n\n<p>We were goofing around and a friend of mine had me in an arm triangle. I suspect he choked me, because I lost consciousness for a few seconds, max 3. While in that state, I kind of had a dream or vision, whatever it is called. It felt like hours. This was a long time ago and I still remember the dream, but can't make sense of it. What I've seen was really interesting and I couldn't just let it go.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm not asking for dream analysis or anything, but the biological/neurological aspect of what happened, so don't get me wrong.<\/p>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p><sub>I'm also new in here, though not to stackexchange, so the tags might need a modification.<\/sub><\/p>\n","question_id":41305,"tags":["neuroscience","brain"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":52,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/EyjiW.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6337/kalfasyan","reputation":145,"display_name":"kalfasyan","accept_rate":60},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TMSvO.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":542,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/542/hermann-ingjaldsson","reputation":586,"display_name":"Hermann Ingjaldsson"},"score":0,"post_id":17324,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399807450,"comment_id":23577,"body":"<a href=\"http://curebird.com/condition/search?keys=dandruff\" rel=\"nofollow\">curebird.com/condition/search?keys=dandruff<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":2,"post_id":17324,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399808046,"comment_id":23578,"body":"Dandruff is dead scalp, i.e. skin. Your skin everywhere is constantly renewing itself. Everwhere else in your body, dead skin gets scraped off on e.g. clothes, things you touch etc. so you don&#39;t notice it - dandruff gets caught in your hair and thus you do notice it. Dandruff is not a condition, it&#39;s a consequence of natural healthy skin turnover. If you aimed to <i>prevent<\/i> it from forming, you would interrupt a natural process and most likely also incur some sort of damage. Thus, the best way is to get rid of it periodically once it has formed - i.e. <i>wash your hair<\/i> ;)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/EyjiW.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6337/kalfasyan","reputation":145,"display_name":"kalfasyan","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":17324,"edited":false,"creation_date":1399809427,"comment_id":23579,"body":"Ok this seems like a natural cause, but Dandruff has other causes such as Seborrheic dermatitis, psoriasis.. The results are similar (dry skin flakes) and they have nothing to do with washing. Some literature state fungi like <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Malassezia_furfur\" rel=\"nofollow\">Malassezia furfur<\/a> as a cause, but it doesn&#39;t seem to be clear evidence for a permanent cure"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/EyjiW.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6337,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6337/kalfasyan","reputation":145,"display_name":"kalfasyan","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":17324,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/TMSvO.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":542,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/542/hermann-ingjaldsson","reputation":586,"display_name":"Hermann