115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":7759,"edited":false,"creation_date":1370175414,"comment_id":11050,"body":"Micheal Shermer shows a few interesting examples of pareidolia in this video: <a href=\"http://youtu.be/8T_jwq9ph8k?t=6m25s\" rel=\"nofollow\">youtu.be/8T_jwq9ph8k?t=6m25s<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/pFhME.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19277,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19277/iayork","reputation":1582,"display_name":"iayork"},"score":0,"post_id":7759,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449514069,"comment_id":69988,"body":"The samurai crab story is probably a myth, spread by Carl Sagan; discussed <a href=\"https://arthropoda.wordpress.com/2010/01/26/samurai-crabs-transmogrified-japanese-warriors-the-product-of-artificial-selection-or-pareidolia/\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> and <a href=\"http://www.thepointradio.org/features-columns/articles/entry/12/9189\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a>, among other places."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1365188612,"creation_date":1365109863,"body":"<p>I think this really is just a case of what you refer to in your question as anthropomorphism. We are very, very good at seeing faces. <a href=\"http://www.cracked.com/quick-fixes/the-3-most-terrifying-faces-drawn-by-nature/\">Here are some more examples<\/a>.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Addendum<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://www.mymodernmet.com/profiles/blogs/jurgen-otto-peacock-spider\">This site<\/a> has pictures of quite a few peacock spiders, and as far as I can tell these are all the same species (The only peacock spider mentioned on Wikipedia is <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peacock_spider\"><em>Maratus volans<\/em><\/a>). <\/p>\n\n<p>The remarkable thing about these images is that individual spiders seem to have very different patterns on thorax and abdomen, and many of these are much less like human faces. This seems to me to weaken the case for some sort of mimicry.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Interesting fact<\/strong>: seeing faces and other forms where they do not exist is a psychological phenomenon called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pareidolia\">pareidolia<\/a>.<\/p>\n","answer_id":7759,"question_id":7758,"up_vote_count":14,"last_edit_date":1365188612},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpj4v.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3053/drosophila","reputation":1073,"display_name":"Drosophila","accept_rate":50},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e440cd36c7e6f7d7fdb348bfb23e3b60?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":816,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/816/mohammad","reputation":263,"display_name":"Mohammad"},"score":0,"post_id":7761,"edited":false,"creation_date":1365111436,"comment_id":9736,"body":"Thanks drosophilia. Do you think that in this particular case, this &#39;face&#39; is used to ward off bigger, (ostensibly animals) who would recognize this as a &#39;face&#39; of some sort? Or do you think it is just a relic of bilateral symmetry?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpj4v.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3053/drosophila","reputation":1073,"display_name":"Drosophila","accept_rate":50},"score":0,"post_id":7761,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e440cd36c7e6f7d7fdb348bfb23e3b60?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":816,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/816/mohammad","reputation":263,"display_name":"Mohammad"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1365111775,"comment_id":9737,"body":"Not sure. Could be both, I think, since bigger predators may inadvertently crush the spider or use it at play. The scary face could stop them from doing that."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d9f9776938888dc91366dc6371544e91?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3258,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3258/stockfisch","reputation":87,"display_name":"Stockfisch","accept_rate":60},"score":0,"post_id":7761,"edited":false,"creation_date":1365158335,"comment_id":9747,"body":"The subtitle of the video you linked to says it is a courtship ritual."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1365110637,"creation_date":1365110637,"body":"<p>In part, the way the spider resembles a human face is due to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetry_in_biology#Bilateral_symmetry\" rel=\"nofollow\">bilateral symmetry<\/a> in the body shape and coloring of the spider. Bilateral symmetry evolved early in the animal kingdom to facilitate streamlining of the body (which makes it move faster in any fluid, including air and water), formation of a central nervous system and a head. Human faces (and bodies) are also bilaterally symmetric, hence the resemblance.<\/p>\n\n<p>Another reason, as you note, is antropomorphism - the ability of humans to see a human face in many natural shapes and colorings. Other animals, including predators probably also have this ability to see faces in nature. This allowed the spider to evolve to imitate a scary face. This is called <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mimicry\" rel=\"nofollow\">mimicry<\/a> and it helps the spider ward off predators. <\/p>\n","answer_id":7761,"question_id":7758,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/xfUY4.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3589,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3589/thomas-white","reputation":158,"display_name":"Thomas White"},"score":5,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1370140925,"creation_date":1370140925,"body":"<p>Peacock spiders certainly aren't mimicking human faces, and I strongly doubt they're mimicking anything at all. As others have noted, it's the combination of a fluke, and some anthropomorphising on your part (easy to do!).<\/p>\n\n<p>The stunning colours and 'dancing' are actually part of a courtship display, and are most likely under strong <a href=\"http://www.plosone.org/article/info%3Adoi%2F10.1371%2Fjournal.pone.0025390\">sexual selection<\/a>, rather than selection for any anti-predator function. The male-limited colours are only on display during courtship, and are otherwise flattened along the abdomen. It's also worth remembering that these spiders are tiny (&lt; 5 mm), so the only other animals that are likely to be able to resolve those patterns in any detail are similarly sized organisms with decent eyesight (i.e. female peacock spiders).<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://nature.berkeley.edu/~maddiegirard34/menu.html\">Madeline Girard<\/a> is in the latter-stages of her PhD on these guys, I'd recommend shooting her an e-mail if you're really interested.<\/p>\n","answer_id":8616,"question_id":7758,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://graph.facebook.com/10154340785368056/picture?type=large","user_type":"registered","user_id":20479,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20479/george-lilley","reputation":8,"display_name":"George Lilley"},"score":0,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41300,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449519642,"comment_id":69991,"body":"<i>Australia has vast areas that have never been inhabited by humans<\/i>? Such as...? Indigenous Australians have roamed the country for a long, long time before white folks occupied the place. And a link to your source would be helpful."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/da1e8af33e12bfa60ea44b3af00c0d03?s=128&d=identicon&r