of blood changing viscosities, I suspect that in living patients blood viscosity is quite constrained, not only by physiological feedback but by the fact that if the blood viscosity changed very much the patient would <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disseminated_intravascular_coagulation\" rel=\"nofollow\">become nonliving<\/a>. Blood circulates constantly, and when it stops circulating it coagulates(which complicates efforts to measure its viscosity, I imagine). Any local effects on blood viscosity would be 'washed away' by the fresh blood arriving every heartbeat. If there's no or very limited blood circulating to the muscular pathology you're interested in the blood viscosity is probably not as significant as the ischemic tissue death that's just about to happen. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41234,"question_id":41177,"up_vote_count":4}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41177/how-much-is-local-blood-non-newtonian-in-pathophysiology","last_activity_date":1449430251,"creation_date":1449091190,"answer_count":1,"title":"How much is local blood non-Newtonian in Pathophysiology?","body":"<p>I am studying the <em>Barus effect / Merrington effect / <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Die_swell\" rel=\"nofollow\">die swell / extrudate swell<\/a><\/em>, which is a characteristic of non-Newtonian viscoelastic liquids (Introduction to the phenomenon <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KcNWLIpv8gc\" rel=\"nofollow\">in this video<\/a>) i.e. the medium responds to the stress $\\sigma$ of irritator with a strain $\\epsilon (= \\Delta l/l)$ that increases until the medium ultimately fails in a local pathology<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>blood has both viscous and elastic components which it can apply in pathophysiological condition\n\\begin{equation}\n\\gamma = \\gamma_{v} + \\gamma_{e}.\n\\end{equation} <\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<h1>#1 Maxwell material model<\/h1>\n\n<ul>\n<li>total shear stress if blood behaves like Maxwell material in local pathophysiological regions\n\\begin{equation}\n\\sigma = \\sigma_{v} = \\sigma_{E} = \\eta \\frac{d \\gamma_{v}}{d t} = G_{M} \\gamma_{E},\n\\end{equation}\nimplying $\\sigma = \\eta \\, d\\gamma_{v}/dt$ and $\\sigma = G_{M} \\gamma_{E}$.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<hr>\n\n<p>I am thinking when blood is not non-Newtonian etc in muscular pathologies and muscular infections. I want to evaluate how much blood is non-Newtonian in particular situations. \nI am interested in muscles and their supply with necessities. <\/p>\n\n<p>How much is local blood non-Newtonian pathophysiologically?<\/p>\n","question_id":41177,"tags":["physiology","hematology","pathophysiology"],"score":2,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":47,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1449430251},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47fb487899f144cf72fc111d30599796?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13043,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13043/wedstrom","reputation":163,"display_name":"wedstrom"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/31f7489ce1ad16353c71abba83ae8be4?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":4747,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/4747/user137","reputation":3897,"display_name":"user137","accept_rate":78},"score":0,"post_id":27736,"edited":false,"creation_date":1421377337,"comment_id":44658,"body":"If they&#39;re clones they&#39;d be pretty much identical. He might have better luck making induced pluripotent stem cells and deriving them as gametes, then making embryos. Still have the same genes as he did, but at least the recessive/dominant allele ratios might change and could get some females out of it. Why not get DNA from the dead embryos?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/47fb487899f144cf72fc111d30599796?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":13043,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/13043/wedstrom","reputation":163,"display_name":