an other <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paraphyly\" rel=\"nofollow\">paraphyletic<\/a> clades of mammal.<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Which came first?<\/li>\n<li>What did their common ancestors look like?<\/li>\n<li>What are their geographical origins?<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n","question_id":13790,"tags":["evolution","zoology","mammals","phylogenetics","speciation"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"protected_date":1449406105,"is_answered":true,"view_count":6703,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1386239650},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2a00c086323b3c362917d5285e0b6282?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":20446,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20446/dexter","reputation":9,"display_name":"dexter"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/41CJK.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":5762,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/5762/the-last-word","reputation":4553,"display_name":"The Last Word","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":41244,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449468379,"comment_id":69959,"body":"I think that the OP has tried to answer the question himself, so why close?"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449379153,"creation_date":1449379153,"body":"<p>You are correct about the top loop being the intronic region of the gene that would be spliced out of the mRNA that was used to make the cDNA and will not have complementarity to the sequence found in the cDNA. <\/p>\n\n<p>You are also correct that because it is cDNA, then it cannot be RNA for the bottom box. Remember that the cDNA will contain what the mature, spliced mRNA contained, 5'-UTR, coding sequence, 3'-UTR and Poly-A (Poly T if this is first strand cDNA) tail, so the bottom answer is likely an exon, as there is complementarity between the genomic DNA and the cDNA at that position where the arrow pointing.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41269,"question_id":41244,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41244/homework-question-confused-about-figure-related-to-cdna-and-gdna","last_activity_date":1449379153,"creation_date":1449303550,"answer_count":1,"title":"Homework Question: Confused about figure related to cDNA and gDNA","body":"<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/2fxDB.jpg\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/2fxDB.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>what is the answer in blank?<\/p>\n\n<p>I think the loop structure for the top blank is an intron.<\/p>\n\n<p>I think RNA is the answer for the bottom blank, but it is cDNA, so it can't be RNA.<\/p>\n\n<p>I cannot figure out what the question is asking. Please help me.<\/p>\n","question_id":41244,"tags":["molecular-biology","dna","homework","cdna"],"score":-2,"down_vote_count":4,"is_answered":true,"view_count":67,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1449378875},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/m27DI.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":14852,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/14852/talha-irfan","reputation":275,"display_name":"Talha Irfan","accept_rate":83},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/INPrd.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":16651,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16651/amr","reputation":4081,"display_name":"AMR"},"score":2,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449378183,"creation_date":1449378183,"body":"<p>This can happen when DNA separates after melting and then reanneals. <\/p>\n\n<p>You likely will not see this in chromosomal DNA in the cell, but I would assume it can happen to RNA molecules sometimes as they are single stranded and can self-anneal. <\/p>\n\n<p>Mostly though, we think about this issue when performing PCR or DNA/RNA hybridization assays. Shorter pieces of DNA will be more likely to bind and anneal incorrectly, especially if the DNA is rapidly cooled after it has been melted.<\/p>\n\n<p>Rapid cooling does not give the DNA time to \"test\" the different combinations of complementarity and sometimes can get stuck in a place where there is very little complementarity.<\/p>\n\n<p>You also need to remember that while A-T G-C hydrogen bonding is favored, bases are able hydrogen bond to other bases, it just makes the double stranded molecule less stable.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41267,"question_id":41266,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41266/degree-of-complementarity","last_activity_date":1449378183,"creation_date":1449372416,"answer_count":1,"title":"Degree of complementarity","body":"<p>Apologies in advance for asking bit naive question. I have looked up for this concept a lot but didn't find anything.\nThe wikipedia (<em>I know its not authentic all the time, but I think works well for definitions atleast<\/em>) <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complementarity_%28molecular_biology%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">page on Complementarity<\/a> says:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>The degree of complementarity between two nucleic acid strands may vary, from complete complementarity (each nucleotide is across from its opposite) to no complementary (each nucleotide is not across from its opposite) and determines the stability of the sequences to be together<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>This is quite new concept for me and how come we can have basepairing between opposite nucleotides if there isn't 100% complementarity? Any evidences behind it?<\/p>\n","question_id":41266,"tags":["molecular-biology","molecular-genetics"],"score":1,"accepted_answer_id":41267,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":22,"up_vote_count":1,"last_edit_date":1449374272},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpFlm.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1765,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1765/rafique","reputation":250,"display_name":"Rafique","accept_rate":33},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1MUb2.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1306,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1306/terdon","reputation":9339,"display_name":"terdon","accept_rate":73},"score":2,"post_id":9647,"edited":false,"creation_date":1375755873,"comment_id":12685,"body":"You seem to be confusing inheritance with being sex linked. The two are not related. While sex linked characteristics are indeed inheritable, not all (or even most) inheritable traits are <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sex_linkage\" rel=\"nofollow\">sex linked<\/a>. As for what a recessive characteristic is, have a look <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recessive_trait\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> (the first hit when you search for &quot;recessive genetic characteristic&quot; in Google."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ef6c1e9a540c28587fe777f9bcf907af?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1231/mcm","reputation":7783,"display_name":"MCM"},"score":5,"is_accepted":true,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/KD6Fx.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3952,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3952/oreotrephes","reputation":4267,"display_name":"Oreotrephes","accept_rate":86},"score":0,"post_id":9649,"edited":false,"creation_date":1375770159,"comment_id":12691,"body":"Fascinating and complex indeed! So even though there are different risk factors for Type 1 based on mother or father having it, you still wouldn&#39;t term it &quot;sex-linked&quot;?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"re