 of protein coding genes the gene overexpressed in the cells. All this is useful to analyze the function of unknown genes. See the figure for a schematic overview (from  Campbell AP Biology Book 8th edition, via <a href=\"https://lowery-dna-tech-project-2012.wikispaces.com/Lynn+Ymker\">this<\/a> website):<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/enwEu.jpg\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/enwEu.jpg\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Technically making a clone means that you generate multiple genetically identical daughter cells from one precursor.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41225,"question_id":41224,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1449215582}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41224/what-does-it-mean-to-clone-a-gene","last_activity_date":1449215582,"creation_date":1449208436,"answer_count":1,"title":"What does it mean to clone a gene?","body":"<p>When I look up information related to the identification of disease genes, texts will often refer to the gene being \"first cloned.\" What does \"clone\" mean in this context? Is it simply a synonym for discovery?<\/p>\n","question_id":41224,"tags":["genetics","molecular-biology","molecular-genetics","human-genetics"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":41225,"down_vote_count":2,"is_answered":true,"view_count":86,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/04d6a6d6294fee4071192df9a41ed92c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"unregistered","user_id":20429,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20429/madi","reputation":6,"display_name":"Madi"},"closed_date":1449457177,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/1YczA.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":9943,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/9943/christiaan","reputation":26721,"display_name":"Christiaan","accept_rate":93},"score":0,"post_id":41221,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449208084,"comment_id":69794,"body":"Welcome to Bio. What cell? A human n