) and just add them up to get the total net charge.<\/p>\n\n<p>In practice you would need to measure it with something like isoelectric focusing, since polypeptides fold and certain groups end up interacting with other groups/being shielded from solvent, meaning you really can't calculate it accurately unless you had structural data and even then it would be extremely difficult. <\/p>\n","answer_id":41214,"question_id":41212,"up_vote_count":1}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41212/how-do-you-calculate-the-charge-on-a-polypeptide-chain-with-changing-ph","last_activity_date":1449178917,"creation_date":1449175592,"answer_count":1,"title":"How do you calculate the charge on a polypeptide chain with changing pH?","body":"<p>I understand the charge placement on the N &amp; C-terminus and also the utilization of the R-side groups in the amino acids.<\/p>\n\n<p>For example,\nWhat is the overall charge for a chain Glu-Cys-Arg-Asp with pH 11.0 buffer?<\/p>\n","question_id":41212,"tags":["biochemistry","proteins","ph"],"score":1,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":29,"up_vote_count":1},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3cfeec7dfb47b3d98c5edf17295e959b?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":81,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/81/poshpaws","reputation":4731,"display_name":"Poshpaws","accept_rate":71},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c33b5588bbd268ce2680853ea79b1a9?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":231,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/231/mgkrebbs","reputation":3086,"display_name":"mgkrebbs"},"score":4,"post_id":1488,"edited":false,"creation_date":1332218119,"comment_id":1845,"body":"<a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Last_universal_ancestor#Features\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia&#39;s article<\/a> does a pretty fair job of summarizing the likely nature of the LUCA."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.