a polymer of two N-acetylglucosamine units:\n<a href=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XDBUl.png\" rel=\"nofollow\"><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/XDBUl.png\" alt=\"enter image description here\"><\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>Homopolysaccharides can be linear chains or branched, as long as they are made up of just one type of sugar unit. A heteropolysaccharide is made up of multiple different monosaccharide units. <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glycosaminoglycan\" rel=\"nofollow\">Glycosaminoglycans<\/a> would be an example of a heterpolysaccharide as they contain two different sugar units.<\/p>\n","answer_id":41211,"question_id":41208,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41208/chitin-homo-or-heteropolysaccharide","last_activity_date":1449171108,"creation_date":1449164315,"answer_count":1,"title":"Chitin, homo or heteropolysaccharide?","body":"<p>My teacher told me that Chitin is a heteropolysaccharide but my book regards it as a homopolysaccharide.I am so confused<\/p>\n","question_id":41208,"tags":["carbohydrates"],"score":2,"accepted_answer_id":41211,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":182,"up_vote_count":2},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/4d7ad26294abfb00f7bc0c1ae4315a11?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":20400,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/20400/eorn","reputation":18,"display_name":"Eorn"},"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d36bad7a6d2ef2a02e558c89e285bf36?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19690,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19690/chitinous-exoskeleton","reputation":302,"display_name":"Chitinous Exoskeleton","accept_rate":50},"score":3,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1449170398,"creation_date":1449170398,"body":"<p>Turgor Pressure(T.P) is defined as the amount of pressure inside a cell solely due to its water content, whereas Osmotic Pressure(Pi) is defined as the pressure required to stop osmotic flow between the cell and a pure solvent when the pressure exerted by water is zero. <\/p>\n\n<p>Osmotic Pressure is often given as the negative of the Osmotic Potential(or Solute Potential) of the Cell.(Because more the solute, more pressure will be required to stop the osmosis, but against the gradient). (1)<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore, it can be easily seen that Osmotic Pressure is solely dependent on the solute concentration of the cell.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>The Total Suction Pressure(S.P)<\/strong> of a Cell is the pressure required outside of a cell to stop the water flow in a pure solvent. <\/p>\n\n<p>The T.P in such a situation would try to reduce the S.P (More the T.P, less would be the pressure on the outside). Whereas, the O.P in such a situation would try to increase the S.P (More the solute inside a cell, more would the water on the outside try to get on the inside)<\/p>\n\n<p>Hence, Mathematically (considering no other pressures to be responsible for Total Suction Pressure)<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>S.P = Pi - T.P<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>This can Also be proved in the following way:<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Water Potential(Psi W):<\/strong> Total Pressure inside a Cell.<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Solute Potential/Osmotic Potential(Psi S):<\/strong> Reduction in Water Potential Magnitude due to addition of a Solute(solute reduces kinetic energy of water due to bonding)<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Pressure Potential(Psi P):<\/strong> Hydrostatic Pressure, i.e, pressure exerted by the water present inside a cell if there were no solute particles.<\/p>\n\n<p>By definition<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Psi W = Psi S + Psi P<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>(We know, Psi S = -Pi) As written above in (1)<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Psi W = -Pi + Psi P<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>(We know, Turgor Pressure is the same thing as Psi P)<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>Psi W = -Pi + T.P<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>Suction Pressure is the negative of Total Pressure inside a Cell<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>(S.P = -Psi W)<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>(Water flows from high water potential to low potential, but from low Suction Pressure to an area of High Suction Pressure)<\/p>\n\n<p>Therefore<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>-S.P = -Pi + T.P<\/strong><\/p>\n\n<p>multiplying by -1<\/p>\n\n<p><strong>S.P = Pi - T.P<\/strong><\/p>\n","answer_id":41210,"question_id":41164,"up_vote_count":3}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41164/relationship-between-turgor-pressure-and-osmotic-pressure","last_activity_date":1449170398,"creation_date":1449067533,"answer_count":1,"title":"Relationship between turgor pressure and osmotic pressure?","body":"<p>I would like to know if there is a relationship between osmotic pressure (inside and outside of a cell) and turgor pressure. If so, is there a way to formalize it mathematically?<\/p>\n\n<p>Thank you in advance,<br>\nEorn<\/p>\n","question_id":41164,"tags":["microbiology","biophysics","cell-membrane","yeast"],"score":3,"accepted_answer_id":41210,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":323,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d36bad7a6d2ef2a02e558c89e285bf36?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":19690,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/19690/chitinous-exoskeleton","reputation":302,"display_name":"Chitinous Exoskeleton","accept_rate":50},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41203/why-guard-cells-need-to-turn-malate-into-postassium-malate-to-become-turgid","last_activity_date":1449160838,"creation_date":1449160838,"answer_count":0,"title":"Why guard cells need to turn malate into postassium malate to become turgid?","body":"<p>According to the Active Potassium Transport Ion concept given by Levitt et.al, stomata open due to turgidity in guard cells. It seems that guard cells turn the starch produced by photosynthesis into malate (which is a stable solute and should increase the osmotic pressure of the cell) but then go on to invest energy to exchange the hydrogen ions of malate with potassium ions.<\/p>\n\n<p>Thus guard cells basically invest energy to turn malate into lots of potassium malate (so that water will enter due to increase in osmotic pressure), but why should such a process evolve if they can become turgid by just producing lots of malate?<\/p>\n","question_id":41203,"tags":["botany","plant-physiology"],"score":0,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":10,"up_vote_count":0},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b5440c34109e218b55c29d2450159ee?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG&f=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":6136,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/6136/21joanna12","reputation":659,"display_name":"21joanna12","accept_rate":46},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":0,"post_id":41200,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449162361,"comment_id":69750,"body":"look at the answer for the cAMP question you asked - you already seem to know the answer...  <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41084/if-so-many-different-hormones-molecules-work-by-activating-adenyl-cyclase-how-d\" title=\"if so many different hormones molecules work by activating adenyl cyclase how d\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/41084/&hellip;<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/-uS0Elf7lRBo/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAE8/R5J8cBgSOg8/photo.jpg?sz=128","user_type":"registered","user_id":16299,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/16299/vance-l-albaugh","reputation":1284,"display_name":"Vance L Albaugh"},"score":0,"post_id":41200,"edited":false,"creation_date":1449162447,"comment_id":69751,"body":"epinephrine (adrenaline) has many target cells though - and the effects are many - rememb